			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Writer behind Fantastic Four reboot now writing Netflix's Death Note series...
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1850800">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Death Note can absolutely be done live action, far more than things like Ghost in the Shell even. The only really outlandish stuff is the Shikigami stuff, and that's no more hard to pull off than a ring-wraith from Lord of the Rings. Anime is just a medium for telling stories, it's not all as crazy as the more ridiculous stuff would make you believe. Though, it might be difficult to make writing in a notebook seem exciting without all the dramatic camera angles and scene cuts.<br />
<br />
Death Note takes place in a completely mundane world with one interesting gimmick. It's exactly the kind of story someone might come up with for a television show of some sort in the west. Personally, I think they should call it The Notebook, just to confuse people. Oh thought you were sitting down to a love story? Nope, detective drama murder fest.<br />
<br />
As for why people want things like this, I think it's because people love the characters and stories, and want people who don't appreciate or understand the medium to love the characters and stories as well. Making it live action makes it mainstream. It introduces new people to something they didn't know they wanted. Now if anyone with some competence would just do it right...<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
As for the actual article. I didn't see the Fantastic Four movie. Was the writing what was bad? Or one of the things that was bad? I suppose the bar is pretty low anyway, after the first few episodes, Death Note sort of stalled.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
